======================================================================
PART 4: H(T) - H(T-v) = 2 * sum mu(C)
======================================================================
The deletion ratio R(T) = sum_v [H(T) - H(T\v)] / (n * H(T))
H(T) - H(T\v) is always EVEN (from Claim A, the factor of 2)

--- n=5 ---
  H(T)-H(T\v) mod 2: {0: 5000}
  H(T)-H(T\v) mod 4: {0: 2874, 2: 2126}
  Always even: 5000/5000 (100.0%)

--- n=6 ---
  H(T)-H(T\v) mod 2: {0: 6000}
  H(T)-H(T\v) mod 4: {0: 3462, 2: 2538}
  Always even: 6000/6000 (100.0%)

--- n=7 ---
  H(T)-H(T\v) mod 2: {0: 2100}
  H(T)-H(T\v) mod 4: {0: 1077, 2: 1023}
  Always even: 2100/2100 (100.0%)

======================================================================
PART 5: WHY 3-CYCLES? The counting structure
======================================================================
  Distinct (c3,c5,c7) triples: 160
  c7 determines H uniquely: checking via OCF
  H = I(Omega, 2) = 1 + 2*alpha_1 + 4*alpha_2 + 8*alpha_3 + ...
  where alpha_k = #{independent sets of size k in Omega}

  H in base 2 (binary expansion via independence sets):
    H=157, I(Omega,2)=75, alpha=[1, 13, 12, 0, 0, 0], binary=0b10011101
    H=145, I(Omega,2)=73, alpha=[1, 12, 12, 0, 0, 0], binary=0b10010001
    H=73, I(Omega,2)=35, alpha=[1, 9, 4, 0, 0, 0], binary=0b1001001
    H=109, I(Omega,2)=53, alpha=[1, 10, 8, 0, 0, 0], binary=0b1101101
    H=37, I(Omega,2)=23, alpha=[1, 7, 2, 0, 0, 0], binary=0b100101

